title: Clinic of Champions at Spring, TX Gymnastics Academy: Elevate One's Skills in World Champions Centre | User | mammothtimes.com
text:
World Champions Centre is excited to announce the Clinic of Champions, a special event for competitive gymnasts from Level 3 to Level 10 and Xcel. This clinic will be held at their expansive 30,000-square-foot facility over a weekend in the summer, offering young athletes a chance to refine their skills with help from experienced coaches. It's all about strengthening their techniques in a friendly and supportive atmosphere. The Centre is dedicated to nurturing young talent and building a community focused on gymnastics excellence. More information about this clinic, as well as other events, can be found on their website.
This gymnastics training center , known for being the home base for Olympic champions like Simone Biles, offers various programs for kids and young adults. These programs range from recreational activities to competitive training, supporting athletes from beginners to those aiming for elite levels. The environment here is all about promoting both physical abilities and mental toughness.
"Offering programs like the Clinic of Champions reinforces our mission to cultivate an environment where young athletes can thrive," said Zach Francis, a representative from World Champions Centre. "We want to provide both our community and athletes from afar with incredible opportunities to grow, learn, and achieve outstanding feats in gymnastics."
For families interested in kids gymnastics programs, World Champions Centre has plenty to offer. They provide recreational classes that are fun and accessible for children as young as 18 months to those as old as 18 years. These programs focus on personal development and fitness, appealing to anyone drawn to gymnastics as either a sport or a form of exercise.
Besides their extensive class offerings, the Centre holds events that invite the community to experience their top-notch facilities. Programs such as open gym sessions and specialty clinics not only showcase their resources but also engage families and athletes in meaningful ways. These community-focused events are a great complement to their main offerings, bringing together people who are passionate about gymnastics.
"The Centre's programs are designed with each participant in mind, creating opportunities for every child to explore gymnastics in a way that suits them best. Be it through competitive teams, special events, or regular classes, our aim is always to nurture and empower," added Francis.
World Champions Centre has strong partnerships with notable sponsors like Athleta and Houston Methodist. These collaborations reflect the Centre's commitment to quality and innovation. By working with organizations such as The Academy and In-Step Dance, they extend their influence beyond traditional gymnastics and incorporate a well-rounded approach to both sport and art.
For athletes interested in career development, the Centre offers job opportunities and recruitable athlete services for personalized guidance. These initiatives help expand access to the sporting industry, giving talented individuals the support and exposure they need. Additional details on job opportunities and recruitable athlete services are readily available on their website.
The Centre doesn't just stop at programs like the Clinic of Champions. They also host the Simone Biles International Invitational, demonstrating their focus on inclusivity and top-tier competition. With over 200 gymnastics classes every week, they provide a structured yet enjoyable way for participants to hone their gymnastic skills. Details of these events and programs can also be explored on their comprehensive site.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=C9RM6tYUUSk&list=TLGGu0yr-MsXUvIxODA0MjAyNQ&t=4s
World Champions Centre stands out as a leading name in gymnastics. With their spacious and modern facility, they enable athletes of all skill levels to pursue their dreams. Under the right guidance and in a nurturing setting, young gymnasts can reach new heights. Those interested can find more details about their programs and events, like the upcoming Clinic of Champions, by checking their website or getting in touch with them directly via their contact page.

title: Rahmanullah Gurbaz's Stunning Century, Afghanistan Crosses 200 -amp
text: punjabkesari.in Friday, December 29, 2023 ‚Äì 10:10 pm (IST) Sports Desk: Afghanistan‚Äôs opener Rahmanullah Gurbaz, playing against UAE on the ground of Sharjah, scored a century in just 50 balls and made his team cross 200. Gurbaz, who scored his first century in the T20 format, started taking notice of the UAE bowlers from the very beginning. He hit shots around the wicket and scored 100 runs with the help of 7 fours and 7 sixes. With this, 22-year-old Gurbaz has completed 68 sixes in 44 T20 matches. This innings of Gurbaz was also special because he had not been able to perform anything special in the last four domestic Twenty20 matches. Gurbaz was playing for Strikers in the Abu Dhabi T10. He scored 0 against Braves and also 0 against Samp Army. In the next match, he was successful in scoring 56 runs but in the last match, he was out again after scoring only 1 run. Now he must be feeling some relief after scoring a century against UAE. First T20 century! A brilliant innings from Gurbaz [#UAEvAFG] [pic.twitter.com/RKkVCbaG5Q] ‚Äì FanCode (@FanCode) [29 December 2023] Talking about the match, Gurbaz and Hazratullah Jazai had come at the opening. When Zazai was out after scoring 13 runs in 16 balls, Gurbaz along with captain Ibrahim Zadran took the score forward. While Gurbaz was successful in scoring 100 runs in 52 balls, Ibrahim Zadran scored 59 runs in 43 balls with the help of 4 fours and two sixes. Azmatullah scored 19 runs on 8 balls. Nabi also contributed 4 runs on 1 ball and scored 203 runs. In reply, UAE had a very bad start. Opener Khalid Shah was out after scoring 0 runs and Mohammad Wasim was out after scoring 4 runs. When the score was 23 in the fifth over, UAE also lost the wicket of Samal. Afghanistan‚Äôs bowlers were excellent during this period. He troubled the UAE batsmen a lot.

author: Ademola Popoola
title: Wike slams activists, says they don't do well in office | Premium Times Nigeria
text: The Minister of the Federal Capital Territory, Nyesom Wike , on Thursday, slammed former Senator Shehu Sani over the latter‚Äôs claim that pro-democracy activists should have taken power in 1999 after the exit of the military. Mr Wike, a former Governor of Rivers State, questioned the performance of Mr Sani as a member of the 8th Assembly, stating that ‚Äúactivists don‚Äôt perform in office‚Äù. The minister said this at the 2024 Annual Lecture and Awards ceremony organised by This Nigeria newspaper Annual Lecture and Gold Prize Award in Abuja on Thursday. The theme of the event was ‚Äú25 Years of Nigeria‚Äôs Unbroken Democracy: Prospects & Possibilities. ‚Äù | | During a panel discussion, Mr Sani, a prominent activist during the struggle against the military in the 90s, narrated how pro-democracy activists shunned the transition plan of the Abudulsalam Abubakar regime, a decision the former lawmaker said allowed the career politicians to take over power. He disclosed that the former military leader urged most of them to participate in the transition process, but they declined. He added that by the time they changed their minds, the career politicians had taken over. Mr Sani said some of the prominent activists, including the late legal luminary, Gani Fawehinmi, Femi Falana and others, declined to participate but that Bola Tinubu, who later became the governor of Lagos in 1999, agreed to participate in the transition process. ‚Äú‚Ä¶And after four years in prison, when we came out from prison, this is where the story is going to begin. Abdulsalam Abubakar invited all who fought for democracy‚Äî‚Äòthat I am going to hand over power to a democratically elected government. I want all of you, the freedom fighters, to come together and take over power.‚Äô At that very time, Gani opposed it. Three times, he invited us; we even refused to answer his calls. ‚ÄúHe didn‚Äôt invite the politicians; they were knocking at his door. After we decided to listen to him, we came and sat down. ‚ÄúBut after our struggle in 1998 and 1999, we said we were not going to cooperate with the military. Gani opposed, Falana opposed, all opposed. It was Tinubu who said if we don‚Äôt get in, who would be there? ‚ÄúBy the time we all agreed to join the politics, politicians had taken over all positions. Gani tried to be president, and Falana tried to be governor of his state, he couldn‚Äôt. I tried to be governor of Kaduna State, I couldn‚Äôt because all the spaces had been taken over,‚Äù Mr Sani said. It was at this point that Mr Wike requested the microphone, stating that just because Mr Sani and others participated in the struggle does not mean power should be handed over to them. ALSO READ: [Journalists, activists react to BBC documentary about Nigerian cleric] Mr Wike said activists often fail at governance, adding that Mr Sani should produce his scorecard as a senator. He said, ‚ÄúThe mere fact that you were an activist does not mean that you do well. Activists have always failed. ‚ÄúActivists have failed. We have seen activists that were given appointments, and yet they failed. When you were a senator, how did you perform? What was your performance as a senator?‚Äù Mr Wike also took a shot at another panellist, Mike Ozekhome, a prominent lawyer, during the diatribe. He asked Mr Ozekhome, a Senior Advocate of Nigeria (SAN), not to pontificate on election matters. ‚ÄúAnd you said something about taking the election side. As an activist, how many times have you rejected briefs, those who have rigged the election, you have always defended them,‚Äù Mr Wike said. Messrs Sani and Ozekhome did not get the opportunity to reply. author: Karen Longwell
title: Snowsquall warning issued for parts of southern Ontario
text:
Heavy, blowing snow continues to hit parts of southern Ontario.
After heavy snowfall dumped over 20 cm in the Barrie area on Thursday, snowsqualls continue to hit the area and communities just north of the GTA, according to Environment Canada.
The lake effect snow off Lake Huron and Georgian Bay is continuing Friday morning,.
Environment and Climate Change Canada issued snowsquall warnings for Barrie, Orillia, Bruce Peninsula, Tobermory, Lindsay, Kawathra Lakes, Midland, Owen Sound, Peterborough, Uxbridge and Beaverton.
Areas in the southwest such as Kitchener, Waterloo, Woodstock and Oxford Country have snowsquall advisories.
The heavy snowfall could bring an additional five to 10 cm of accumulation.
There will be poor visibility at times in heavy snow and blowing snow.
Lake effect snow is expected to move south of the area later Friday morning.
The lake effect snow will return this weekend over some areas. Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow.
Rapidly accumulating snow will make travel difficult. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow.
Environment Canada suggests drivers consider postponing non-essential travel until conditions improve.
Areas in red have snowsquall warnings, yellow areas are watches and the grey is a weather statement for possible heavy snow.
Lead photo: Dylan Freedom
